It invariably begins with ‘quod' ‘whereas ;' c. g. in Gaius iv. 39 ‘quod Aulus Agerius Numerio Ne- gidio hominem vendidit 3’ or ⁸ apud Numerium Negidiurn hominem deposuit) Occasionally the place of the demonstratiois taken bya praescriptio (pro actore), and sometimes even the latter is prefixed to or worked into the former; its use is confined to formulae upon actions in which the plaintiff is entitled from the defendant to anumber or variety of acts prima facie hanging together, but of which one only, or at least not all, are claimed in the present action. By the prae- scriptio, beginning ‘ea res agatur, let the present trial relate exclusively to so and so,’ the plaintill reserved his right of action upon the other acts, or those subsequently to fall due, which would otherwise have been eonsumed; it being a presumption of Roman law (capable, however, of being rebutted by the insertion ofa praescriptio in the formula) that when a man instituted an aetion, it comprised all his claims against the defendant, prospective no less than present, sofar at least as they related to the present ground of action, and already had at least a potential existence. Two examples are given by Gaius. In the one, a man to whom an annuity is payable, say, every six months, sues for a half year's instaltnent, using the praescriptio ‘ea res agatur cuius rei dies fuit ς’ in the other, the purchaser of an estate, ' claimlng that it shall be conveyed to him by mancipation, reserves to himself the n'ght of subsequently demanding its mere traditio hya praescriptio in the form ‘ea res agatur de fundo mancipando'
